      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, im studying for my con law exam and kinda stuck on judicial philosophy. can u explain what originalism is and what some of the main arguments for it are?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Originalism is a judicial philosophy that interprets the Constitution based on its original meaning at the time it was written. Proponents argue that it ensures stability and predictability in the law by preventing judges from imposing their personal views. They also believe it respects the democratic process, as the Constitution's meaning was determined by the people and their representatives at the time of its creation. Originalists argue that this approach limits judicial activism and maintains the separation of powers, as it prevents judges from making policy decisions. They also contend that it provides a clear and objective standard for interpreting the Constitution, reducing the risk of arbitrary or biased decisions.",
      "source": "target",
